<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> MULTIPLAYER-Notes<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.50)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10500'>Charles "Kakita" Bickford</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10500&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 23, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> The reason I was looking forward to playing this new trading card game was not only the &#8220;Lord of theRings&#8221;-setting but also the fact of the multiplayer possibility. Compared to other trading card games with multiplayer options ( like Magic, Warlord, Rifts) the &#8220;LotRs&#8221;rulebook encourages the players to use the &#8220;more people, more fun&#8221; version of the game. <br>
The great advantage is that the &#8220;all against one&#8221;-strategy of multiplayer games is still there, because all shadow players fight against on person at a time, but the unfair early knockout, which generally occurs at Magic-games and results in an annoyed and bored player who only can watch the rest of a long multiplayer game and who thinks &#8220;Why do they always go against me first?&#8221;. In this gamethe fellowship player is responsible for all his actions and the more risky he plays the greater is the possibility of an early defeat. But he can control this for himself. <br>
The next advantage is that mostly all decks that work against one player is ceven compatible in a multiplayer game, with some exeptions: <br>
- A Discard-strategy deck is not so effective against more players <br>
- Your deck must contain at least 80 cards (40/40) to minimize the empty deck befor site 9. <br>
- Generally, each designed deck for two player games is less effective in multiplayer games , because you have to split your shadow power, but it is no disadvantage compared to other card games, because the other Shadow players may support you and invent even stronger combos together, which would normally not work alone, because of your limited slots in your deck. The most problems has the fellowship with a combination of Isengard/Sauron/Ringwraith conditions an minions at one time. <br>
In short.: Your refined and tuned strategy will be weakened a bit in multiplayer games, but new possibilities arise with combos beween different shadow cultures or support of the same shadow culture (simply because more players mean a greater pool of fitting shadow cards at a given situation). So the need of exchanging cards every time you play multiplayer games is not there. <br>
<br>
Disadvantages: of &#8220;LotRs&#8221;-Multiplayer games: <br>
First, like every multiplayer trading card game, you need a lot of time. Our average 4-5 player sessions last 2-3 hours. But you will rarely have time to go to the restrooms in that period of time, because compared to other card games, you are always involved in action either on the shadow or the fellowship side. No games like &#8220;untap my forest , play an elf, wait 5 minutes, and so on.&#8221;. So this disadvantage can be ignored. <br>
Construction of your &#8220;adventure path&#8221;-deck ( or also called &#8220;site side&#8221; -deck) is nearly futile, because no one can anticipate who will play the next site. Cards like &#8220;Thror´s Map&#8221; or &#8220;Pathfinder&#8221; are strongly recommended. <br>
The moving limit in Multiplayer-games is ridiculous. Show me a sane hobbit who moves 5 times in one turn in a 5-player match. In my opinion it is impossible to use your full move limit im MP-games, so all cards, which allows you to increase your move limit can be thrown out of your deck. <br>
<br>
Bidding: <br>
There are only two reasons of high bidding (3-5 burdens) in LotRs- 2-player game: <br>
First the &#8220;Prancing Pony&#8221; for downloading (please exuse this phrase) Aragorn and second to go last when playing Nazguls to enhance the adventures path with &#8220;Bree Streets&#8221; and &#8220;Ford of Bruinen&#8221;, to play the Nazguls more easily. <br>
In MP-games the need for biding is not really necessary, because at least one of the players WILL download Arargorn and so play the &#8220;Prancing Pony&#8221;, so you can use this site for your Aragorn, too, without biding any burden , because of the high corruption danger in MP-games. As the Nazgul-player, with the need for the go last strategy, forget it because of the confusen if site laying (see above). <br>
The ony reason to bid high and start first is, when you do not have a &#8220;sneak and hide and run&#8221; strategy, because then it can matter a lot when you are the first player, who has the theoretical chance of reaching site 9 first. That is even more important, when site 8 is &#8220;Shores of Nen Hithoel&#8221;, which prevent you from moving again by spotting 5 orc minions.( You must know that 5 orcs ARE THERE FOR SURE in a MP-game). <br>
And be aware: In a MP.Game burdens are even more dangerous than in an 2-player game, because they grow faster. <br>
<br>
Playing Cards and Companion Size: <br>
There can´t be a rigt or wrong size of your fellowship. It all depends on your strategy. But more than five companions are a lot in higher site regions, an you cant trust your luck that your opponent can not use all tokens like in 2-player game. The poo, will always be depleted in a most efficient way to hurt you most. <br>
The fastest way to communicate asa shadow players in the shadow phase is to announce clockwise the needed token number and the amount of minions he can play with the demanded tokens (mayby even strengths of that minions), so the first shadow player who will play announces last. That&#8217;s the quickest and uncomplicated way to distribute the tokens, but it is not really the funniest way of play. The discussion between the shadow players is the most interesting part of the game ( maybe I post an article about that later). <br>
So, if you want a fast, straight game, restrict the discussion an play, but if you have time and want a pleseant, intriguing match, win your game by bluffing the best in the shadow phase, make coalitions and timely limited alliances, and break them at the right time. <br>
A big advanatge is the fast card draw and play rate. That means you have 2-4 shadow phases and 1 fellowship phase, followed by 2-4 more shadow phases. HAVE MANY CARDS (100- 120) in your deck. Have in mind that you can`t play shadow cards in all shadow phases, if you don´t want to run out of cards (exept when playing Moria orcs, then the strategy is playing all you can). You will notice that after the 3rd consecutive shadow phase your fellowship cards will be increased in your hand. You can customize your hand for your next fellowship phase during the many shadow phases, by playing shadow cards and discarding useless cards in the regroup phase. So the cahnce of drawing strong cards for your fellowship phase is extremley better than in a 2-player game. <br>
Avoid the biggest mistake: It is very alluring to use most of the twilight token pool when you are the first shadow player. This automaticly results in an fight always against the player to your left. So there is a general tendency only to weaken one and the only player. Look around, evaluate the situation and decide which opponent is to be weakend or which opponent is to be saved from elimination only because he is still a strong shadow player against an other opponent (or against you!). This is the 2-sided coin in LotRs. A weak fellowship is not automatically a weak Shadow player, because the two sides act differently. <br>
<br>
Moving: <br>
Different decks need different mobing strategies, that is obvious! But it is important to adapt your movment to the rest of the players. When you are to fast, in al MP-game, you are target number one and you are at sites where paaying minions is more effective, because of the roaming costs, which have not to be payed at higer sites. Go with the mass, or even stay behind, then wait for the right moment to run away. <br>
The most interesting point in MP-games is the fact, that, all our MP-matches were concluded with a &#8220;9-site victory&#8221;. So do not speculate to make a &#8220;Shadow Side Victory&#8221;, by being the last surviver. You can only eliminate some of your foes. It is nearly impossible to crush them all. So do not stay behind to far. <br>
<br>
Best Multiplayer-Cards: <br>
<br>
Condition: Worry ( Imagine 3 players have a Uruk Hai deck) <br>
Condition: Goblin Domain ( a lot of nice red counters are needed) <br>
Condition: Under the watching Eye (works against all players, exept you) <br>
Event: Sleep, Caradhas ( the Shadow players will kill you) <br>
Site: Shores of Nen Hithoel (see above) <br>
Site: Summit of Amon Hen ( imagine a 5-player game with the fellowship players burdens of 6 à 35 new cards for the ultimate showdown) <br>
<br>
